# Hello there!
#
# We care about making our git history clean, maintainable and easy to access for
# all our contributors. Commit messages are very important to us,
# which is why we have a strict commit message policy in place.
# Please use the following guidelines to format all your commit
# messages:
#
#   <type>: <subject>
#
# Please note that:
# + <type> describes the kind of change that this commit is providing.
#   Allowed types are:
#   * release: New version release
#   * chore: A code change that external user won't see (e.g.: CI update or changes in `.gitignore`/`.prettierrc` files)
#   * feat: A new feature
#   * fix: A bug fix
#   * docs: Documentation related changes
#   * refactor: A change that improves the code without changing its behavior
#   * perf: A change improving performance
#   * test: Adding new test or making changes to existing test
#
# + <subject> is a very short description of the change, in the following format:
#   * imperative, present tense (eg: use "add" instead of "added" or "adds")
#   * no capitalized first letter
#   * no dot (.) at the end
#
# Thank you
